\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {10}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Ensemble Forecast Residual Diagnostics}. Three complementary assessment panels validate model assumptions and forecast reliability. \textit  {Left panel} (Residuals vs.\ Predicted): Residuals scatter symmetrically around zero across the full prediction range $[0, 1]$, with consistent band width $(\pm 0.2)$, confirming homoscedasticity and absence of systematic prediction bias. \textit  {Center panel} (Residual Distribution): The empirical histogram closely matches the normal density overlay (red dashed curve), indicating approximately Gaussian residuals. The kernel density estimate (blue curve) reveals a unimodal, centered distribution. \textit  {Right panel} (Normal Q-Q Plot): Empirical quantiles align with the theoretical normal line throughout the central range, with minor tails-off in extreme quantiles. This pattern is standard for finite-sample estimation and does not compromise the validity of inference. Collectively, these diagnostics support the parametric and distributional assumptions underlying conformal interval construction and confidence quantification.}}{63}{figure.caption.32}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:forecast_residuals}{{10}{63}{\textbf {Ensemble Forecast Residual Diagnostics}. Three complementary assessment panels validate model assumptions and forecast reliability. \textit {Left panel} (Residuals vs.\ Predicted): Residuals scatter symmetrically around zero across the full prediction range $[0, 1]$, with consistent band width $(\pm 0.2)$, confirming homoscedasticity and absence of systematic prediction bias. \textit {Center panel} (Residual Distribution): The empirical histogram closely matches the normal density overlay (red dashed curve), indicating approximately Gaussian residuals. The kernel density estimate (blue curve) reveals a unimodal, centered distribution. \textit {Right panel} (Normal Q-Q Plot): Empirical quantiles align with the theoretical normal line throughout the central range, with minor tails-off in extreme quantiles. This pattern is standard for finite-sample estimation and does not compromise the validity of inference. Collectively, these diagnostics support the parametric and distributional assumptions underlying conformal interval construction and confidence quantification}{figure.caption.32}{}}
